{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Rhapsody Debug Toolbar</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody includes a powerful, non‑intrusive debug toolbar that appears at the bottom of every page
        when the application is in <strong>development mode</strong> (<code>APP_ENV=development</code>).
        It gives you real‑time insight into your application's performance, database queries, session data,
        middleware execution, dependency resolution, and more – all without cluttering your design.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/40 border-l-4 border-blue-500 dark:border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4">
        <strong class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">💡 Tip:</strong>
        <span class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">The toolbar is only injected into HTML responses. JSON/API responses are never altered.</span>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Toolbar Overview</h2>
    <p>
        The toolbar is divided into clickable tabs, each displaying a specific category of debug information.
        It also includes a persistent header that shows key metrics at a glance.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-4 my-4 font-mono text-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center space-x-4">
            <span class="bg-indigo-600 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded">Rhapsody v1.0</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Request <span class="text-green-400">200</span></span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Logs</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Database <span class="text-yellow-400">12 Queries</span></span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Session</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Cache</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Performance</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Environment</span>
            <span class="ml-auto text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Time: 231 ms</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 flex items-center">
                <span class="w-3 h-3 bg-green-500 rounded-full mr-1"></span>
                45%
            </span>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Header Widgets</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Request Status</strong> – HTTP status code of the response (green = 200, red = 4xx/5xx).</li>
        <li><strong>Execution Time</strong> – total time taken to process the request (in milliseconds).</li>
        <li><strong>Memory Peak</strong> – a visual bar showing peak memory usage relative to the <code>memory_limit</code>; colour‑coded: green (safe), amber (warning), red (critical).</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Request Tab</h2>
    <p>
        The Request tab provides a comprehensive snapshot of the incoming HTTP request. It's your go‑to for
        debugging routing issues, inspecting headers, or reproducing a request via cURL.
    </p>

    <h3>Request Overview</h3>
    <p>At the top, you'll find essential request metadata:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Method</strong> – HTTP verb (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.)</li>
        <li><strong>Full URL</strong> – the complete URL of the request (including protocol, host, and query string)</li>
        <li><strong>Client IP</strong> – the IP address of the client making the request</li>
        <li><strong>Timestamp</strong> – exact time the request was received</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Route Details</h3>
    <p>Displays information about the matched route:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Path</strong> – the URI path (after stripping <code>APP_BASE_URL</code>)</li>
        <li><strong>Controller</strong> – the class handling the request</li>
        <li><strong>Action</strong> – the method being called</li>
        <li><strong>Parameters</strong> – dynamic route parameters (e.g., <code>user_id</code> from <code>/users/{user_id}</code>)</li>
        <li><strong>Middleware</strong> – the list of route‑specific middleware (shown as a chain, e.g., <code>auth → guest</code>)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If no route matched, the panel shows a helpful "No route matched" message – ideal for debugging 404s.</p>

    <h3>Request Headers</h3>
    <p>
        All HTTP headers sent by the client are displayed in a clean key‑value table. This includes standard headers
        like <code>User-Agent</code>, <code>Accept</code>, <code>Content-Type</code>, and any custom headers your
        application or client may send.
    </p>

    <h3>Query Parameters</h3>
    <p>
        If the request URL contains a query string (e.g., <code>/users?page=2&limit=10</code>), the parameters are
        displayed in a key‑value table. This is useful for debugging pagination, filters, or other GET parameters.
    </p>

    <h3>Request Body</h3>
    <p>
        For POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE requests, the raw request body is displayed:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>If the body is valid JSON, it is automatically <strong>pretty‑printed</strong> for readability.</li>
        <li>If the body is plain text (e.g., form data), it is shown as‑is.</li>
        <li>If the request had no body, this section is omitted.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Copy cURL Command</h3>
    <p>
        At the bottom of the Request tab, there is a <strong>📋 Copy cURL</strong> button. Clicking it generates a
        complete <code>curl</code> command that replicates the current request – including method, URL, headers,
        and body. This is invaluable for:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Reproducing bugs in a terminal</li>
        <li>Sharing a request with a colleague for debugging</li>
        <li>Testing API endpoints independently</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-950/40 border-l-4 border-green-500 dark:border-green-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4">
        <strong class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">Pro Tip:</strong>
        <span class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">
            On Windows, use <code>curl.exe</code> instead of <code>curl</code> to avoid PowerShell's alias.
            The command generated in the toolbar will automatically use <code>curl.exe</code> on Windows.
        </span>
    </div>

    <h4>Why use cURL instead of just viewing page source?</h4>
    <p>
        You might wonder: <em>"I can already see the page source in my browser – why do I need a cURL command?"</em>
        Here's why it's much more powerful:
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-4">
        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-400">🔁</span> Reproduce anywhere
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Run the exact same request on any machine – your local terminal, a server, or a colleague's laptop.
                No browser, no cookies, no extensions.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-yellow-400">✏️</span> Modify and test
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Tweak headers, change parameters, or alter the request body to test different scenarios quickly.
                No need to navigate through forms or click around.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-purple-400">📦</span> See the full response
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Page source only shows the HTML body. cURL shows <strong>everything</strong> – status code, headers,
                cookies, and timing details. Perfect for debugging APIs.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-indigo-400">📤</span> Share with teammates
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Instead of saying <em>"click this button and fill out that form"</em>, you can share a one‑line
                command that reproduces the bug exactly.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-red-400">⏱️</span> Measure performance
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Add timing flags to measure DNS lookup, connection time, and total response time – metrics you
                can't get from page source.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h5 class="text-white font-bold flex items-center gap-2">
                <span class="text-cyan-400">🤖</span> Automate testing
            </h5>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mt-1">
                Use the cURL command in CI/CD pipelines, load‑testing scripts, or monitoring tools to verify
                your endpoints automatically.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-950/40 border-l-4 border-amber-500 dark:border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4">
        <strong class="text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300">🧠 In a nutshell:</strong>
        <span class="text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300">
            <strong>View Page Source</strong> = quick visual inspection of the HTML structure.<br>
            <strong>cURL Command</strong> = a complete, reproducible snapshot of the entire HTTP transaction.
        </span>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Logs Tab</h2>
    <p>
        Shows the last 50 lines of your PHP error log and Apache error log (or web server log).
        The log file paths are defined in <code>config.php</code> under the <code>logging</code> key.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-950/40 border-l-4 border-amber-500 dark:border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4">
        <strong class="text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300">Note:</strong>
        <span class="text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300">If a log file is not found or not readable, the toolbar will show a message indicating that.</span>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Database Tab</h2>
    <p>
        Lists every SQL query executed during the request, along with:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>SQL</strong> – the raw query string</li>
        <li><strong>Parameters</strong> – bound values (as JSON)</li>
        <li><strong>Execution Time</strong> – time taken (in milliseconds)</li>
        <li><strong>Caller</strong> – the file and line where the query was initiated</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>N+1 Query Detection</h3>
    <p>
        The toolbar automatically flags potential <strong>N+1 query patterns</strong>. This happens when the same
        query structure (after normalising literal values) is executed <strong>more than 3 times</strong> in a single request.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>If detected, a warning box appears at the top of the Database tab.</li>
        <li>Each flagged query is marked with a warning icon (<code>⚠️</code>) in the list.</li>
        <li>See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/performance">Performance &amp; Caching</a> guide for strategies to fix N+1.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/40 border-l-4 border-blue-500 dark:border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4 text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-300">
        <h4 class="font-bold">N+1 Queries Explained</h4>
        <p>
            N+1 queries occur when your code executes one query to fetch a list of records, and then another query for each record to fetch related data.
        </p>
        <h5 class="font-bold mt-2">Simple analogy</h5>
        <p>
            Imagine you go to a library and ask:<br>
            "How many books do you have?" (1 query)<br>
            The librarian tells you there are 10 books.<br>
            Then you ask:<br>
            "What are the titles of each of the 10 books?"<br>
            ... and you ask that 10 separate times (10 more queries).<br>
            That's 11 queries total — an N+1 problem.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Session Tab</h2>
    <p>
        Shows the contents of <code>$_SESSION</code> in a clean key‑value table.
        Nested arrays are rendered as indented lists for readability.
        Values are colour‑coded:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><span class="text-green-400">true</span> / <span class="text-red-400">false</span> – booleans</li>
        <li><span class="text-gray-500">null</span> – null values</li>
        <li><span class="text-yellow-400">Object</span> – objects (class name shown)</li>
        <li><span class="text-cyan-400">Keys</span> – array keys</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is invaluable for debugging authentication state, flash messages, and user‑specific data.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Cache Tab</h2>
    <p>
        Displays performance metrics for the framework's cache system (driven by <code>Cache::remember()</code> and <code>Cache::get()</code>).
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Hits</strong> – number of successful cache lookups</li>
        <li><strong>Misses</strong> – number of cache misses (values not found)</li>
        <li><strong>Total Requests</strong> – hits + misses</li>
        <li><strong>Hit Ratio</strong> – percentage of requests that were hits</li>
        <li>A progress bar visualises the ratio with colour coding:
            <ul>
                <li><span class="text-green-400">Green</span> – &gt; 70% (healthy)</li>
                <li><span class="text-yellow-400">Yellow</span> – 40‑70% (room for improvement)</li>
                <li><span class="text-red-400">Red</span> – &lt; 40% (cache may be underused or ineffective)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        If your application is not using caching, the stats will remain zero – that's expected.
        See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/caching">Caching documentation</a> to add cache to your code.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Performance Tab</h2>
    <p>
        This tab is powered by a <strong>React</strong> component (<code>PerformancePanel</code>) and provides a
        high‑level dashboard of your application's performance metrics, all in one place.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Execution Time</strong> – same as the header, with a progress bar scaled to 1000ms</li>
        <li><strong>Memory Usage</strong> – current memory peak (MB) with a bar scaled to 16MB</li>
        <li><strong>Database Queries</strong> – total query count, scaled to 100 queries</li>
        <li><strong>Cache Hit Ratio</strong> – the same cache ratio as the Cache tab</li>
        <li><strong>N+1 Detection</strong> – summary of any potential N+1 patterns, with a collapsible detail list</li>
        <li><strong>Route / Controller</strong> – shows the matched route (same as Request tab)</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Environment Tab</h2>
    <p>
        This comprehensive tab gives you deep insight into your application's runtime environment,
        middleware pipeline, and dependency injection container. It is your go‑to for debugging bootstrapping
        issues, middleware misconfigurations, and circular dependencies.
    </p>

    <h3>Environment Variables</h3>
    <p>
        Displays all environment variables (<code>$_ENV</code>) in a sortable table.
        Sensitive values (passwords, secrets, API keys) are partially masked for your security.
        This is useful for verifying that your <code>.env</code> settings are correctly loaded.
    </p>

    <h3>Middleware Tracer</h3>
    <p>
        Shows every middleware that ran during the request, in the exact order they were executed:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Type</strong> – <span class="text-blue-400">Global</span> (runs on every request) or <span class="text-purple-400">Route</span> (assigned to specific routes)</li>
        <li><strong>Class</strong> – the middleware class name</li>
        <li><strong>Route</strong> – the route path (for route middleware)</li>
        <li><strong>Duration</strong> – execution time in milliseconds (colour‑coded: green &lt; 20ms, yellow 20‑50ms, red &gt; 50ms)</li>
        <li><strong>Total Middleware Time</strong> – sum of all middleware execution times</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        This is invaluable for pinpointing slow middleware that might be causing request latency, or for
        verifying that your middleware stack is correctly ordered.
    </p>

    <h3>Container Inspector</h3>
    <p>
        Visualises the service container's dependency resolution for the current request:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Service</strong> – the resolved class (or interface)</li>
        <li><strong>Duration</strong> – time taken to resolve (colour‑coded like middleware)</li>
        <li><strong>Called By</strong> – the class that requested this service (helps trace dependencies)</li>
        <li><strong>Status</strong> – <span class="text-green-400">✅ Resolved</span> (success) or <span class="text-red-400">⚠️ Circular</span> (if a circular dependency was detected)</li>
        <li><strong>Total Resolve Time</strong> – sum of all resolution times</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        If you see a <span class="text-red-400">⚠️ Circular</span> status, the toolbar will also show
        the circular chain (e.g., <code>A → B → C → A</code>), making it easy to fix.
        This is particularly useful for debugging complex dependency graphs in large applications.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-950/40 border-l-4 border-green-500 dark:border-green-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-4">
        <strong class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">Pro Tip:</strong>
        <span class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">
            The Environment tab is perfect for diagnosing "silent" failures – when a page loads but behaves unexpectedly.
            Check the middleware order and container resolutions to catch misconfigurations quickly.
        </span>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Enabling / Disabling the Toolbar</h2>
    <p>
        The toolbar is automatically injected when <code>APP_ENV</code> is set to <code>development</code>.
        To disable it in development (e.g., to test raw HTML output), you can temporarily comment out the toolbar
        injection in <code>index.php</code> (around line where <code>Toolbar</code> is instantiated).
    </p>
    <p>
        In production (<code>APP_ENV=production</code>), the toolbar is <strong>never</strong> shown, regardless of
        the <code>development</code> setting. This is a security feature.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Extending the Toolbar</h2>
    <p>
        The toolbar is designed to be extensible. You can add your own panels by hooking into the
        <code>Debug::end()</code> method and injecting custom data into the <code>$this->data</code> array.
        The React components (<code>PerformancePanel</code>, <code>MemoryProfiler</code>) are also open to extension.
    </p>
    <p>
        For advanced use, refer to the source code in <code>vendor/arout/rhapsody-core/src/Debug.php</code>
        and <code>vendor/arout/rhapsody-core/src/Toolbar.php</code>.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <div class="bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-950/40 border-l-4 border-green-500 dark:border-green-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">Happy debugging!</strong>
        <p class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 mt-1">
            The toolbar is your best friend during development. Use it to catch performance bottlenecks,
            inefficient queries, middleware misconfigurations, circular dependencies, session anomalies,
            and request‑level issues before they reach production.
        </p>
    </div>

{% endblock %}